{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17655932","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17655932"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:07:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:07:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18695"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18695","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18695"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0.05,0,0.05,0.77]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11427"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76865"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11427","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11427"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18695"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62370"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10535"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26466"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26469"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76865","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76865"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThirst is a vital homeostatic mechanism that maintains body fluid balance. The sensation is triggered by specific physiological changes.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary stimulus for thirst?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Decreased blood pressure","Decreased plasma sodium","Reduced salivary flow","Increased plasma glucose","Increased plasma osmolality"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased plasma osmolality\u003C/strong\u003E is the primary stimulus for thirst. Specialised osmoreceptors in the hypothalamus detect changes in plasma osmolality as small as 2% above the normal range of 285-295 mOsm/kg. When activated, these receptors trigger both thirst sensation and antidiuretic hormone release to maintain fluid homeostasis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased blood pressure\u003C/strong\u003E - While severe hypotension can influence fluid intake, it is not the primary trigger for thirst\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReduced salivary flow\u003C/strong\u003E - Dry mouth may cause discomfort but does not directly stimulate central thirst mechanisms\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased plasma glucose\u003C/strong\u003E - While hyperglycaemia can lead to osmotic diuresis and eventual thirst, it is not the direct stimulus\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased plasma sodium\u003C/strong\u003E - Low sodium would decrease osmolality and typically reduces rather than stimulates thirst\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe osmoreceptors are exquisitely sensitive to changes in extracellular fluid tonicity and form the primary physiological mechanism for maintaining proper fluid balance through thirst regulation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Osmoreceptors in the hypothalamus detect increased plasma osmolality and trigger thirst.","Normal plasma osmolality is maintained between 285-295 mOsm/kg.","A 2% increase in plasma osmolality is sufficient to trigger thirst sensation."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data"